	<h1> Basics of the Web using HTML and CSS</h1>
	<div class="lesson">
	<h2>Lesson 1 Concepts</h2>
		<div class="concept">
		<div class="concept-title">
			<h3>How The Web Works</h3>
		</div>
			<p>
				The web or internet is a series of computers that communicate with each other through servers. When you go to a www.google.com for example your browser requests that web page's HTML document from the server and then displays it on your screen. Check out the video below from <a href="http://www.dontfeartheinternet.com/01-not-tubes/">Don't Fear the Internet</a> for more details.
			</p>
	
		<div class="aid">
			<iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/24006296?color=ffffff&title=0&byline=0&portrait=0" width="560" height="315" allowfullscreen>
			</iframe>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="concept">
	<div class="concept-title">	
		<h3>HTML</h3>
	</div>
		<p>
				HTML stands for <em>Hypertext Markup Language</em>. HTML documents contain text that the browser can read and then display as a web page. Check out the video below for more details
		</p> 
	<div class="aid">
			<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/mzPxo7Y6JyA" allowfullscreen></iframe>
	</div>
	</div>
		<div class="concept">
		<div class="concept-title">
			<h3>Tags and Elements</h3>
		</div>
			<p>
				HTML is made of text which contains elements and tags. Check out the video below which explains this in detail. Don't worry about CSS we will learn more about this later.
			</p>
		<div class="aid">
			<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/naowH2LzuVg" allowfullscreen></iframe>
		</div>
		</div>
		<div class="concept">
		<div class="concept-title">
			<h3>Inline Vs. Block</h3>
		</div>
			<p>
				Finally HTML elements are either inline or block. Block differs itself from inline in that block elements form an "invisible block" in which to display content. In the previous video you already may remembering hearing about some these elements known as divs or spans.
			</p>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="lesson">
		<h2>Lesson 2 Concepts</h2>
		<div class="concept">
		<div class="concept-title">
			<h3>Developer Tools</h3>
		</div>
			<p>
				Most web browsers have a way to view the code the webpage was written in. For example, in Gooogle, the <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nOEw9iiopwI">Chrome Developer Tools</a> (DevTools for short), are provide for web developers for deep access into the internals of the browser and other web applications.
			</p>
		</div>
		<div class="concept">
		<div class="concept-title">
			<h3>DOM</h3>
		</div>
			<p>
				The Document Object Model (DOM) is a programming interface for HTML documents. It provides a way that the structure can be accessed from programs so that they can change the style and content. The DOM is used by browser to translate HTML tags in tree-like structure.
			</p>
		</div>
		<div class="concept">
		<div class="concept-title">
			<h3>CSS</h3>
		</div> 
			<p>
				Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) is a language used for the styling of a webpage. CSS works in conjunction with HTML forming divisions and layouts of the page. Looking closely you could break down any webpage into sections or boxes.
			</p>
		</div>
	</div> 
	<div class="lesson">
		<h2>Lesson 3 Concepts</h2>
		<div class="concept">
		<div class="concept-title">
			<h3>CSS Positioning</h3>
		</div>
			<p>
				There are several CSS properties that deal with positioning. I recommend reading Alvaro Castro-Castilla's blog on <a href="http://blog.fourthbit.com/2013/11/27/essential-css-positioning">Essential CSS Positioning</a>. He goes over all the basic concepts of the topic. 
			</p>
		<div class="aid">
			<img src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/fourthbit-blog/2013-11-27-essential-css-positioning-for-everyone/absolute.png" alt="This is an example of positioning."/>
			<p class="citation">
				Castro-Castilla, Alvaro. Absolute Positioning. Digital image.<br> Blog.fourthbit.com. N.p., 27 Nov. 2013. Web. 27 June 2016.
			</p>
		</div>
		</div>
		<div class="concept">
		<div class="concept-title">
			<h3>CSS Classes and ID</h3>
		</div>
			<p>
				In CSS, a class selector name preceded by a period [.] and an ID selector is a name preceded by a hash character [#]. You can use class and id selectors to modify mutiple HTML tags of same name rather than modifying them individually.
			</p>
		</div>
		<div class="concept">
		<div class="concept-title">
			<h3>CSS divs and spans</h3>
		</div> 
			<p>
				The difference between &lt;span&gt; and &lt;div&gt; is that a span element is in-line, such as inside a paragraph. Whereas a div (division) element is block-line and used to group larger chunks of code. each div forms a block around the code allowing it to modified. 
			</p>
		</div>
	</div> 
